04778nam a22007215i 9780231553568DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20212021nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2020045611  a97802315535687 a10.7312/schn200342doi  a(DE-B1597)590371  a(OCoLC)1200833022  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aBF575.A6bS36 2021 4aBF575.A6 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a152.4/62231 aSchnittker, Jason, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUnnerved :bAnxiety, Social Change, and the Transformation of Modern Mental Health /cJason Schnittker. 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2021  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tChapter One. The Significance and Meaning of Anxiety -- tChapter Two. A Late Modern History of Anxiety -- tChapter Three. The Evolving Science of Anxiety and Depression -- tChapter Four. Anxiety Disorders in the United States -- tChapter Five. Family Change and Cohort Differences in Anxiety -- tChapter Six. The Decline in Religious Participation -- tChapter Seven. Uncertain Attachments -- tChapter Eight. Status Anxiety and Growing Inequality -- tChapter Nine. The Ascent of Anxiety as a Therapeutic Target -- tChapter Ten. The Past, Present, and Future of Fear -- tMETHODOLOGICAL APPENDIX -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAnxiety is not new. Yet now more than ever, anxiety seems to define our times. Anxiety disorders are the most common psychiatric disorders in the United States, exceeding mood, impulse-control, and substance-use disorders, and they are especially common among younger cohorts. More and more Americans are taking antianxiety medications. According to polling data, anxiety is experienced more frequently than other negative emotions. Why have we become so anxious?In Unnerved, Jason Schnittker investigates the social, cultural, medical, and scientific underpinnings of the modern state of mind. He explores how anxiety has been understood from the late nineteenth century to the present day and why it has assumed a more central position in how we think about mental health. Contrary to the claims that anxiety reflects large-scale traumas, abrupt social transitions, or technological revolutions, Schnittker argues that the ascent of anxiety has been driven by slow transformations in people, institutions, and social environments. Changes in family formation, religion, inequality, and social relationships have all primed people to be more anxious. At the same time, the scientific and medical understanding of anxiety has evolved, pushing it further to the fore. The rise in anxiety cannot be explained separately from changes in how patients, physicians, and scientists understand the disorder. Ultimately, Schnittker demonstrates that anxiety has carried the imprint of social change more acutely than have other emotions or disorders, including depression. When societies change, anxiety follows.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aAnxiety disorders. 0aAnxietyxSocial aspects. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh  aanxiety.  ahistory of psychology.  amental health.  apsychology.  apublic health.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertColumbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021z978311073907740uhttps://doi.org/10.7312/schn2003440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780231553568423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780231553568/original  a978-3-11-073907-7  Columbia University Press Complete eBook-Package 2021b2021  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  